            },
            "answer_text": "Not if you accept the formal definition that a sentence must contain a finite verb and a subject \u201cdoing\u201d the verb. The well known shortest sentence is \u201cHe Wept\u201d or was it \u201cJesus wept\u201d? The shortest sentence possible, two words. (Infinitives and participles are not \u201cfinite\u201d verbs.) Hence, although \u201cYes\u201d occurs frequently as a stand-alone statement, that in itself doesn\u2019t make it into a sentence. If you accept that def\u2019n\u2026 And if you don\u2019t, then you could infer that any combination of words is a sentence, But in reality many of those will be phrases rather than sentences. ",
